25 SECTION 1B.(a) The title of Article 23 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes reads
26 as rewritten:
27 "Article 23.
28 "Right to Natural Death; Brain Death.Advance Directive For A Natural Death ("Living Will")."
29 SECTION 1B.(b) G.S. 90-320 reads as rewritten:
30 "§ 90-320. General purpose of Article.
31 (a) The General Assembly recognizes as a matter of public policy that an individual's
32 rights include the right to a peaceful and natural death and that a patient or the patient's
33 representative has the fundamental right to control the decisions relating to the rendering of the
34 patient's own medical care, including the decision to have life-prolonging measures withheld or
35 withdrawn in instances of a terminal condition. This The purpose of this Article is to establish an
36 optional and nonexclusive procedure by which a patient or the patient's representative may
37 exercise these rights. A military advanced medical directive executed in accordance with 10
38 U.S.C. § 1044 or other applicable law is valid in this State.
39 (b) Nothing in this Article shall be construed to authorize authorizes any affirmative or
40 deliberate act or omission to end life other than to permit the natural process of dying. Nothing
41 in this Article shall impair or supersede impairs or supersedes any legal right or legal
42 responsibility which any a person may have to effect the withholding or withdrawal of
43 life-prolonging measures in any lawful manner. In such respect the provisions of this Article are
44 cumulative."
45 SECTION 1B.(c) Article 23 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by
46 adding a new section to read:
47 "§ 90-320.1. Combining health care planning documents.
48 (a) An advance directive under this Article may be combined with any other advance
49 health care planning document, such as:
50 (1) A health care power of attorney prepared pursuant to Article 3 of Chapter 32A
51 of the General Statutes.
